Inflation in Europe jumps over food
Accelerating inflation in the euro area is due to the constant rise in food prices in the first place.
November price growth in 13 eurozone countries was above higher expectations, with annual inflation of 3.1 percent registered after 2.6 percent in October, the Luxembourg Bureau of the Union said.
The official forecast was only 3%, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the US, British and Canadian issuant, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the key interest rate, saying that the reduction, along with rising raw material prices and falling unemployment, would lead to an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below two percent, but close to them.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in an absurd situation: it must “deter on inflation” so that it does not have to do business in this matter later.
In Germany, November’s inflation is a 15.3 percent record, rising from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent in Spain.
Inflation in the eurozone has swung up because of skyrocketing food and energy prices.
The term prices of wheat increased by 88 percent, and the soybean exchange rate has reached its highest value since 1973.
In 2007, it was also necessary to pay significantly more for edible oil and dairy products.
The price of oil on world markets rose 52 percent this year, and last month it cost one barrel of black gold almost $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will jump in 2008 from 2.1 percent this year to 2.5, but will fall to 1.9 in 2009.
According to analysts, the level of 12 months will remain close to 3 percent in the next 3-4 months, but its average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to lower interest rates twice during 2008.
