It's not Warhol's boxes
Whoever combines the terms Sweden and the wooden crates does not think about Andy Warhol, but on Ikea.
Or yes?
Wooden crates produced in Sweden cast dark shadows on the list of Warhol's works.
Most of his on the list of ninety-four "Brillo boxes" of the Stockholm type are forgeries.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" a few months ago expressed doubts about the authenticity of Warhol's "Brillo boxes" from 1968, the internal research of the Moderna Museetus Museum in Stockholm comes with a result that brought dismisorship; six "Brillo boxes" that was donated by the Moderna Museetus museum in 1995 by its former director Pontus Hultun, are copies - as are the most of the other "Brillo boxes" of the Stockholm type.
Previous events are a tangled, confusing chain of art and curatorial events.
Warhol made his first Brillo boxes in New York City in 1964, painting wooden crates based on the red-and-blue design of the Brillo soap powder paper boxes.
In 1968, the exhibition of his works at Moderna Museet performed hundreds of Brillo boxes made a cardboard – with Warhol’s approval. These did not come (from financial reasons) from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo factory.
They were not works of art, but about their originals, mere exhibition pieces.
Warhol apparently also gave permission in 1968 to make several wooden Brills in Sweden, but they are not on display at Moderna Museet.
Witnesses at the time are now talking about fifteen crates that rightly entered artistic and auction history as authorized originals - "Andy Warhol's Brills" with the designation Type Stockholm.
Some of them were auctioned for more than $100 000 at auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the museum, Pontus Hultén, later falsely claimed that in 1968, approximately one hundred crates were produced and exhibited in Sweden, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, 105 Hulten crates were made in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg only in 1990.
By that time, Warhol was dead three years after his death.
Lars Byström, the top conservator of Moderna Museet, explored in addition to the six Brill boxes that are owned by the museum, also three Brill boxes from the Swedish private collection, two of which were made in Sweden in 1968 and after their plywood boards were painted with basic paint and sanded, they were painted with an oil white paint with a brush.
On the contrary, it became clear from the structure of copies from 1990 that the paint was applied with a painting roll directly on the plywood board without prior prime of the coating - in addition, it is an acrylic and not an oily color.
"These crates have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from Warhol's official list of Brillo boxes," said Moderna Museet's director Lars Nrittve: "If the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York doesn't come to other conclusions, Moderna Museet will have to classify six boxes from its exhibition collections as "exclusive material - copies.""
In July, the Authentication Board announced that it would deal with these "proper allegations" that had been made in the case of soap powder boxes.
But the organization is still in relentful silence.
